<DOC><DOCNO> AP900623-0043 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-06-23-90 0542EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i PM-Obit-Harwood 1stLd-Writethru a0460 06-23 0338</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Obit-Harwood, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0460,0345</SECOND><HEAD>Soprano Elizabeth Harwood Is Dead At Age 52</HEAD><NOTE>Eds: SUBS 7th graf pvs, `Ms. Harwood...' to CORRECT opera title.Pick up 8th graf, `Returning to...'</NOTE><DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Elizabeth Harwood, one of Britain's best-knownoperatic sopranos in the 1960s and 1970s, has died after a battlewith cancer, her family said. She was 52.   Ms. Harwood, who specialized in lyric and coloratura roles andthe music of Mozart, died Friday at her home in Fryerning, 20 milesnortheast of London. She sang with nearly all the top Britishoperatic companies and appeared regularly in leading roles at theprestigious annual music festival in Salzburg, Austria in the early1970s.   With her striking good looks and a radiant stage presence, Ms.Harwood delighted audiences at opera houses around the world.   Her mother, a professional soprano, gave her singing lessonswhen she was a child, and she later studied at the Royal ManchesterCollege of Music at Manchester in northern England.   She made her operatic debut in 1960, singing Second Boy in ``DieZauberflote'' at Glyndebourne in southern England.   In 1963 she scored her first major success, as the CountessAdele in Rossini's ``Count Ory.'' In 1960, she won Britain's prizedKathleen Ferrier memorial award for singing, in 1965 was jointwinner of the Verdi Competition at Busseto in Italy.   Ms. Harwood first appeared at the Salzburg Festival in 1970,when she sang the role of Constanze in Mozart's 1782 opera ``TheAbduction from the Seraglio'' and that of Fiordiligi in ``Cosi fantutte.''   Returning to Salzburg in 1972, she sang the countess in a newproduction of Mozart's ``The Marriage of Figaro'' conducted byHerbert von Karajan. He continued to invite her to Salzburg forseveral years.   She sang Constanze at Milan's La Scala in 1972.   In the late 1970s her health began to deteriorate. Ms. Harwood'slast public performance was in November 1989 at the Bath Festivalin western England.   She married businessmen Julian Royle in 1966. The couple had oneson.</TEXT></DOC>